3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* delivered_hdr 3
6/* SUMMARY
7/* process Delivered-To: headers
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* #include <delivered_hdr.h>
10/*
11/* DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *delivered_hdr_init(stream, offset, flags)
12/* VSTREAM *stream;
13/* off_t offset;
14/* int flags;
15/*
16/* int delivered_hdr_find(info, address)
17/* DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *info;
18/* const char *address;
19/*
20/* void delivered_hdr_free(info)
21/* DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *info;
22/* DESCRIPTION
23/* This module processes addresses in Delivered-To: headers.
24/* These headers are added by some mail delivery systems, for the
25/* purpose of breaking mail forwarding loops. N.B. This solves
26/* a different problem than the Received: hop count limit. Hop
27/* counts are used to limit the impact of mail routing problems.
28/*
29/* delivered_hdr_init() extracts Delivered-To: header addresses
30/* from the specified message, and returns a table with the
31/* result. The file seek pointer is changed.
32/*
33/* delivered_hdr_find() looks up the address in the lookup table,
34/* and returns non-zero when the address was found. The
35/* address argument must be in internalized form.
36/*
37/* delivered_hdr_free() releases storage that was allocated by
38/* delivered_hdr_init().
39/*
40/* Arguments:
41/* .IP stream
42/* The open queue file.
43/* .IP offset
44/* Offset of the first message content record.
45/* .IP flags
46/* Zero, or the bit-wise OR ot:
47/* .RS
48/* .IP FOLD_ADDR_USER
49/* Case fold the address local part.
50/* .IP FOLD_ADDR_HOST
51/* Case fold the address domain part.
52/* .IP FOLD_ADDR_ALL
53/* Alias for (FOLD_ADDR_USER | FOLD_ADDR_HOST).
54/* .RE
55/* .IP info
56/* Extracted Delivered-To: addresses information.
57/* .IP address
58/* A recipient address, internal form.
59/* DIAGNOSTICS
60/* Fatal errors: out of memory.
61/* SEE ALSO
62/* mail_copy(3), producer of Delivered-To: and other headers.
63/* LICENSE
64/* .ad
65/* .fi
66/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
67/* AUTHOR(S)
68/* Wietse Venema
69/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
70/* P.O. Box 704
71/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
72/*--*/
73

91/* Global library. */
92
93#include <record.h>
94#include <rec_type.h>
95#include <is_header.h>

97#include <header_opts.h>
98#include <delivered_hdr.h>
99#include <fold_addr.h>
100
101 /*
102 * Application-specific.
103 */
104struct DELIVERED_HDR_INFO {
105 int flags;
106 VSTRING *buf;
107 VSTRING *fold;
108 HTABLE *table;
109};
110
111#define STR(x) vstring_str(x)
112
113/* delivered_hdr_init - extract delivered-to information from the message */
114
115DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *delivered_hdr_init(VSTREAM *fp, off_t offset, int flags)
116{
117 char *cp;
118 DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *info;
119 const HEADER_OPTS *hdr;
120
121 /*
122 * Sanity check.
123 */
124 info = (DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *) mymalloc(sizeof(*info));
125 info->flags = flags;
126 info->buf = vstring_alloc(10);
127 info->fold = vstring_alloc(10);
128 info->table = htable_create(0);
129
130 if (vstream_fseek(fp, offset, SEEK_SET) < 0)
131 msg_fatal("seek queue file %s: %m", VSTREAM_PATH(fp));
132
133 /*
134 * XXX Assume that mail_copy() produces delivered-to headers that fit in
135 * a REC_TYPE_NORM record. Lowercase the delivered-to addresses for
136 * consistency.
137 *
138 * XXX Don't get bogged down by gazillions of delivered-to headers.
139 */
140#define DELIVERED_HDR_LIMIT 1000
141
142 while (rec_get(fp, info->buf, 0) == REC_TYPE_NORM
143 && info->table->used < DELIVERED_HDR_LIMIT) {
144 if (is_header(STR(info->buf))) {
145 if ((hdr = header_opts_find(STR(info->buf))) != 0
146 && hdr->type == HDR_DELIVERED_TO) {
147 cp = STR(info->buf) + strlen(hdr->name) + 1;
148 while (ISSPACE(*cp))
149 cp++;
150 cp = fold_addr(info->fold, cp, info->flags);
151 if (msg_verbose)
152 msg_info("delivered_hdr_init: %s", cp);
153 htable_enter(info->table, cp, (void *) 0);
154 }
155 } else if (ISSPACE(STR(info->buf)[0])) {
156 continue;
157 } else {
158 break;
159 }
160 }
161 return (info);
162}
163
164/* delivered_hdr_find - look up recipient in delivered table */
165
166int delivered_hdr_find(DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *info, const char *address)
167{
168 HTABLE_INFO *ht;
169 const char *addr_key;
170
171 /*
172 * mail_copy() uses quote_822_local() when writing the Delivered-To:
173 * header. We must therefore apply the same transformation when looking
174 * up the recipient. Lowercase the delivered-to address for consistency.
175 */
176 quote_822_local(info->buf, address);
177 addr_key = fold_addr(info->fold, STR(info->buf), info->flags);
178 ht = htable_locate(info->table, addr_key);
179 return (ht != 0);
180}
181
182/* delivered_hdr_free - destructor */
183
184void delivered_hdr_free(DELIVERED_HDR_INFO *info)
185{
186 vstring_free(info->buf);
187 vstring_free(info->fold);
188 htable_free(info->table, (void (*) (void *)) 0);
189 myfree((void *) info);
190}
